# 📘 OOP (DETAILED MASTER LEVEL) 🔥

---

# 🧠 1️⃣ What is OOP? (DETAILED)

## ✅ Definition

**Object-Oriented Programming (OOP)** is a programming paradigm where we organize code using **objects and classes**, instead of just functions and logic.

👉 It focuses on:

* Real-world modeling
* Code reusability
* Maintainability
* Scalability

---

## 🔍 Why OOP is Needed?

Without OOP:

* Code becomes messy
* Hard to maintain
* Reuse is difficult

With OOP:

* Modular code
* Reusable components
* Easy debugging

---

## 🌍 Real-world Analogy

| Real World   | Java      |
| ------------ | --------- |
| Car          | Object    |
| Car Design   | Class     |
| Driving      | Method    |
| Color, Speed | Variables |

---

# 🧱 2️⃣ CLASS (DETAILED)

## ✅ Definition

A **class** is a blueprint/template used to create objects.

👉 It defines:

* Variables (data)
* Methods (behavior)

---

## 💡 Key Points

* No memory allocated until object is created
* Logical structure only

---

## 💻 Code

```java
class Car {
    String color;
    int speed;

    void drive() {
        System.out.println("Driving...");
    }
}
```

---

# 🧍 3️⃣ OBJECT (DETAILED)

## ✅ Definition

An **object** is a real-world entity created from a class.

👉 It has:

* State (variables)
* Behavior (methods)

---

## 💡 Memory Concept

```java
Car c1 = new Car();
```

👉 Internally:

* `c1` → reference (stack)
* Object → heap memory

---

## 💻 Example

```java
public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Car c1 = new Car();

        c1.color = "Black";
        c1.speed = 100;

        c1.drive();
    }
}
```

---

# 🔐 4️⃣ ENCAPSULATION (DETAILED 🔥)

## ✅ Definition

Encapsulation is the process of **binding data + methods together** and **restricting direct access**.

👉 Achieved using:

* `private` variables
* `public` getters/setters

---

## 🎯 Purpose

* Data hiding
* Control access
* Security

---

## 🌍 Real-world Example

ATM:

* You cannot directly change balance
* You must use methods

---

## 💻 Code

```java
class Employee {
    private int salary;

    public void setSalary(int salary) {
        if (salary > 0) {
            this.salary = salary;
        }
    }

    public int getSalary() {
        return salary;
    }
}
```

---

## 🧠 Internal Working

* Data → hidden
* Access → controlled via methods

---

## 🔥 Interview Q&A

👉 Why encapsulation?

* Security
* Validation
* Flexibility

👉 Can we make class fully encapsulated?

* Yes (all variables private + getters/setters)

---

# 🧬 5️⃣ INHERITANCE (DETAILED 🔥)

## ✅ Definition

Inheritance allows one class to **acquire properties of another class**.

👉 Keyword: `extends`

---

## 🎯 Purpose

* Code reuse
* Avoid duplication
* Maintain hierarchy

---

## 🌍 Real-world Example

* Animal → Dog → Puppy

---

## 💻 Code

```java
class Animal {
    void eat() {
        System.out.println("Eating...");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void bark() {
        System.out.println("Barking...");
    }
}
```

---

## 🧠 Types of Inheritance

1. Single
2. Multilevel
3. Hierarchical

👉 Java does NOT support multiple inheritance (class) ❌
👉 But supports via interface ✅

---

## 🔥 Interview Q&A

👉 Why multiple inheritance not supported?

* Ambiguity problem (Diamond problem)

---

# 🎭 6️⃣ POLYMORPHISM (DETAILED 🔥🔥)

## ✅ Definition

Polymorphism means **one name, many forms**

---

## 🔹 Types

---

## 1. Compile-time (Method Overloading)

👉 Same method name, different parameters

```java
class Calc {
    int add(int a, int b) {
        return a + b;
    }

    double add(double a, double b) {
        return a + b;
    }
}
```

---

## 2. Runtime (Method Overriding)

👉 Child class overrides parent method

```java
class Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Animal sound");
    }
}

class Dog extends Animal {
    void sound() {
        System.out.println("Dog barks");
    }
}
```

---

## 🧠 Key Concept

```java
Animal a = new Dog();
a.sound();
```

👉 Output → Dog barks
👉 Decided at runtime

---

## 🔥 Interview Q&A

👉 What is dynamic method dispatch?

* Runtime decision of method

👉 Can we override static method?

* No (method hiding)

---

# 🧩 7️⃣ ABSTRACTION (DETAILED 🔥🔥)

## ✅ Definition

Abstraction means **hiding implementation details and showing only functionality**

---

## 🎯 Purpose

* Reduce complexity
* Focus on essential features

---

## 🌍 Real-world Example

Mobile:

* You use apps
* Don’t know backend logic

---

## 🔹 Using Abstract Class

```java
abstract class Vehicle {
    abstract void start();

    void fuel() {
        System.out.println("Fuel needed");
    }
}
```

---

## 🔹 Using Interface

```java
interface Vehicle {
    void start();
}
```

---

## 🧠 Difference (IMPORTANT)

| Feature              | Abstract Class | Interface       |
| -------------------- | -------------- | --------------- |
| Methods              | Both           | Mostly abstract |
| Multiple inheritance | No             | Yes             |
| Constructor          | Yes            | No              |

---

## 🔥 Interview Q&A

👉 When to use interface?

* Multiple inheritance
* Loose coupling

👉 100% abstraction possible?

* Yes (using interface)

---

# 💻 FULL REAL-WORLD EXAMPLE (ADVANCED)

```java
interface Payment {
    void pay();
}

class CreditCard implements Payment {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Paid via Credit Card");
    }
}

class UPI implements Payment {
    public void pay() {
        System.out.println("Paid via UPI");
    }
}

public class Main {
    public static void main(String[] args) {
        Payment p;

        p = new CreditCard();
        p.pay();

        p = new UPI();
        p.pay();
    }
}
```

